##Drug companies 'skimming' Redesivir business opportunities, counterfeit compliance questioned

Micro Signal China Business Journal

Function introduction, grow in step with Chinese enterprises, talk with business leaders, spread business ideals, serve business people, "China Business News" control of the absolute voice of Chinese business.

Gao Yujing reporting from Beijing

The Public Company that announced the successful imitation of Remdesivir, a potential drug against the new coronavirus that is still in clinical trials, has seen its share price plummet.

Recently, the Shanghai Stock Exchange respectively made the decision to give regulatory attention to Borui medicine (Url) and the then Secretary Wang Zhengye to give notice of criticism of the decision, the property of Zhongda (600704.Sh ) and then secretary Chen Haibin to give notice of criticism. The Shenzhen Stock Exchange issued a warning letter to Hainan 000566.sz  .

Three listed companies were punished, the trigger is related to the inaccurate disclosure of research and development of Ridgway, in violation of the "stock listing rules. ".

Before the announcement, the punishment will follow. Before and after, a-share market sentiment was accurately "ignited" by the concept of Ridgway. BOREAL's shares peaked at 72.38 yuan on Feb. 14, up 66.66 percent from their close on Feb. 11, before the announcement. The shares peaked at 10.29 yuan per share on Feb. 18, after trading was capped at 349,000 shortly after the announcement. The company's shares hit an all-time high of 5.82 yuan per share on Feb. 13, after the company said in a statement to investors on the Shanghai Stock Exchange's e-interactive platform that its subsidiary produced the redswell project.

The challenges of Patent Licensing and qualified production run through the Chinese pharmaceutical companies interested in copying Ridgeville.

Compulsory license for patent

Bourse in the BORUI pharmaceutical, product Zhongda, Hainan Haiyao regulatory penalties, in the relevant documents, the listed companies involved did not obtain the United States Gilead company authorized.

The licensing refers to the US Gilead (Gilead) R & D Ridgeway process applied for patent licensing.

Gilead filed nine patents for COVID-19 between 2011 and 2018, according to the patent information bulletin on fighting pneumonia, published by the State Intellectual Property Office on Feb. 14.

Before that, cheng Yongshun, director of the beijing-based Intellectual Property Development Center, told China Business Daily: "generally speaking, a new drug needs to go through the strict examination and approval of technical indicators such as safety, reliability and production stability by the State Food and Drug Administration before it can be produced and marketed. In the case of a patented new drug, the Generic Drug Company may only consider granting a patent license to the patent holder after the patented drug has been approved for the market."

But as the global epidemic continues to spread, mention is increasingly being made of the compulsory licensing of patented medicines in the Doha Declaration, adopted unanimously by members of the WTO  .

According to an industry source familiar with the global biopharmaceutical business, "Many countries have laws on compulsory licensing of pharmaceutical patents, which means that when a major public health disaster occurs, pharmaceutical manufacturers can apply for exemption from patent restrictions and be authorized by the state to make copies, which is common practice in every country. "

In fact, the last time we had a compulsory patent for public health purposes was for Gilead's antiviral drug Oseltamivir Phosphate Phosphate Phosphate Phosphate.

Oseltamivir phosphate, developed by Gilead and marketed by Roche worldwide, is a patented original drug that has therapeutic and preventive effects against influenza a, influenza B, H5N1, H9N2 and other subtypes of avian influenza influenza. Oseltamivir phosphate was recommended by the WHO for use in the 2005 flu pandemic and is listed as a reserve drug in many countries around the world, according to the influenza A virus subtype H5N1.

At the time, Roche licensed the manufacture and sale of Oseltamivir phosphate to Shanghai Pharmaceutical Group in 2005 and Shenzhen Dongyangguang Industrial Development Co. in 2006, under pressure from the government to enforce production licenses. Under the agreement at the time, Oseltamivir phosphate produced by the two Chinese companies could only be supplied for state storage and government procurement, while Roche's original research products continued to be sold commercially.

In fact, according to the international practice of the pharmaceutical industry, when authorizing production, the LICENSOR has to pay a certain "royalty" and "production license fee" to the patentee. But the license fees for the period have been vague for two Chinese drug companies that obtained the right to manufacture and sell Oseltamivir phosphate under a compulsory patent license. However, in a notice released on February 9,2017, Dongyangguang Pharmaceutical (01558.HK ) , a unit of Shenzhen Dongyangguang Industrial Development Co. , Ltd. , said that, "The company pays royalties to licensors of Oseltamivir phosphate based on sales. The controlling shareholder is permitted to use the relevant Oseltamivir phosphate patent until the expiry date (the core patent expired in 2017) or has been declared invalid. The last patent expires on 202410 March."

In the past two years, the State Intellectual Property Office and the Food and Drug Administration have conducted detailed studies on the implementation of compulsory licensing of drug patents, but there have been no new regulations, a drug patent researcher who declined to be named told reporters. The current rules, which are based on the Patent Law of the People's Republic of China and the 2012 measures for compulsory licensing of patents, are posted on the State Intellectual Property Office's website.

According to public information, Articles 6 and 7 of Chapter 2, "submission and acceptance of compulsory license requests" , of the measures for compulsory license for patent implementation, which came into effect on May 1,2012, relate to public interests and the situation of medicines.

Article 6 provides that, "In the event of a state of emergency or exceptional circumstances, or for the purpose of public interest, the competent department under the State Council May, in accordance with Article forty-nine of the Patent Law, recommend to the State Intellectual Property Office to grant compulsory license to the entity designated by it that meets the conditions for implementation. "

The Patent Law referred to in the above regulation is the version that came into effect on October 1,2009, and its forty-nine articles are basically consistent with the above provisions.

"The main procedure for the implementation of compulsory licensing of pharmaceutical patents is that an application is submitted by an enterprise and the State examines and approves whether the conditions stipulated in the public health crisis have been met. If the review is approved, the licensing fee shall be agreed between the implementer and the right holder and then implemented, and the use shall cease once the crisis has been resolved. If there is a dispute, an administrative action may be brought", the drug patent researcher said.

As Xiamen University, head of the Intellectual Property Institute at the University of California, San Diego, and others put it in a proposal to use patent enforcement to address current public health issues -- as in the case of the COVID-19, "There are two channels through which compulsory licensing can be initiated in our country: First, companies with productive capacity apply to the State Intellectual Property Office for Compulsory Licensing; and second, the Public Health Authority recommends that the State Intellectual Property Office decide to issue compulsory licensing to the entity designated by the Public Health Authority. "

The copy program is suspect

In addition to patent licensing, the three listed companies subject to regulatory penalties for the commercial batch production of assets in doubt.

The announcement of progress in the development of antiviral drug, which was made public on February 12th, said: "The company has successfully developed the process and preparation technology for the production of RADICIVIR BPC and has already mass-produced Radicivir BPC. Mass production of Radicivir BPC is in progress. "

"The company has completed the first batch production of Radicivir, and has a large-scale production capacity of 3.5 million units per year, " Hainan Haiyao said in a Feb. 15 announcement

In response to questions from investors on the "Shanghai Stock Exchange e interactive" platform on the morning of February 13, CPC said, jiangsu Keben Pharmaceutical Co. , Ltd. , a holding subsidiary of the company, is in the pre-construction stage of the project of "1000000000 doses of Red Xiwei 10T / preparation" , which is a special anti-pneumonia medicine for COVID-19 pneumonia.

The head of a Pharmaceutical Research Institute of a pharmaceutical company told the reporter that under normal circumstances, the generic drug research and declaration process includes at least eight steps, namely: 1 (II) obtaining the patent authorization of the right holder; (III) submitting an application for the selection of Reference Preparations to the Drug Examination Center; (IV) conducting non-clinical research, it includes prescription technology study (pilot test, pilot test, mass production for commercial production) , quality study, stability study, pharmacology and toxicology study Submit an application to the FDA for a clinical trial; conduct a clinical bioequivalence test; and undergo on-site Verification (including three dynamic on-site process checks to confirm that all processes are in compliance with the submitted registration process) ; After the data of the clinical trial is qualified, apply for the approval of drug registration and listing.

According to the exchange's regulatory and punishment documents, boreal pharmaceuticals, the company's research and development of Radzivir, are non-clinical research stages. Specifically, Borui pharmaceutical is under way, Ridgway Research and development of small and medium-sized, medium-sized batches of pilot production. Products in the large subsidiary of the company, is the research and development of Ridgway Project for the record (including product development, clinical trials) .

The reporter learned from the General Supervision Office of the Project Management Department of the R & D Department of a pharmaceutical enterprise that in the preparation for the R & D of Generic Drugs, reference preparations and raw materials will be procured and tested under laboratory conditions using an experimental system, it includes prescription process exploration, small-scale pilot production verification process, pilot production and process verification, and other tests related to the evaluation of drug safety and stability. Generally speaking, these experimental products do not involve commercial production, sales, so not in the original research patent rights protection mechanism.

According to the procedures for the selection and determination of reference preparations for chemical generics, published by the State Food and Drug Administration in March 2019, Generics Manufacturers and R & D Enterprises Shall, prior to research, applications should be submitted to the State Food and Drug Administration through the reference preparation selection application platform.

The reporter inquired about the public information on the platform of the State Food and Drug Administration, and did not find the application registration of the reference preparation related to Radzivir.

The procedure for the selection and determination of reference preparations of Chemical Generic Drugs stipulates that the original research drugs of imitation mainly fall into the following categories: first, the original research drugs listed on the domestic market, second, the drugs produced in China by foreign original research enterprises or by technology transfer, and third, the original research drugs have not been imported.

If domestic drug companies are going to comply with the regulations to copy Ridgeville, it will probably be through Gilead's technology transfer license to Chinese drug companies to do so, said the analyst, who is familiar with the global biopharmaceutical business. If it is through the technology transfer channel to make a generic version of Radzivir, the authorized Chinese pharmaceutical company only needs to conduct stability studies at the plant that is preparing to produce Radzivir, through the test to understand the preparation in temperature, humidity, light exposure and other environmental factors under the influence of changes, after the drug regulatory departments on-site process inspection qualified, before the final report to the FDA listing, and then put into production.

"The apprentice will have to pass the exam to get started, " the industry source said.

Two clinical trials of COVID-19 are still under way in Wuhan, and subjects are being added to the group.

The two trials were designed to be completed in late April and early May.
